UTM conversion with map preview."]}]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"What the two formats mean"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["A coordinate is just an angle. Decimal degrees write that angle as a single number with a fractional part: ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"48.858420"}],". DMS breaks the same angle into three integer-ish parts: 48 full degrees, then 51 minutes (1/60 of a degree each), then 30.3 seconds (1/60 of a minute each)."]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["The math is the same in both cases. To go from DD to DMS, take the integer part as degrees, multiply the fractional part by 60 to get minutes (integer part of the result), then multiply ",["$","em",null,{"children":"that"}]," fractional part by 60 to get seconds. To go the other way, add everything up: degrees + minutes/60 + seconds/3600."]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"When to use which format"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Use DD"}]," for anything digital — APIs, spreadsheets, Google Maps URLs, GIS files, navigation apps. It's the modern standard and avoids parsing the ° ' \" symbols."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Use DMS"}]," for paper nautical charts, aviation publications, land-survey documents, and historical references. Many published surveys still cite DMS."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Convert when crossing formats"}]," — e.g., reading a coordinate off an old chart and pasting it into Google Maps, or copying a phone's coordinate into a printed expedition report."]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"How much precision do you really need?"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Each decimal place of latitude or longitude shrinks your error by roughly a factor of ten. A practical rule:"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"3 decimals (~110 m) — enough to identify a city block."}],["$","li",null,{"children":"4 decimals (~11 m) — enough to identify a building."}],["$","li",null,{"children":"5 decimals (~1.1 m) — enough to identify a parking space. This is what most smartphone GPS chips realistically deliver."}],["$","li",null,{"children":"6 decimals (~11 cm) — the de facto storage format, but the real-world accuracy is rarely better than ~1 m."}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"For DMS, one second of latitude is about 31 meters, and one decimal of a second is about 3 meters. Old surveys often give whole-second precision — perfectly adequate for showing a landmark, less so for guiding a drone."}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Hemispheres and signs — common mistakes"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"DD uses signs: positive for North/East, negative for South/West. DMS uses hemisphere letters (N, S, E, W) instead. Mixing the two is the single most common mistake in conversion. Two examples to keep in mind:"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["Sydney Opera House — ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"-33.8568, 151.2153"}]," in DD ↔ ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"33° 51' 24.5\" S, 151° 12' 55.1\" E"}]," in DMS. The S flips the sign, not the magnitude."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["Statue of Liberty — ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"40.6892, -74.0445"}]," in DD ↔ ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"40° 41' 21.1\" N, 74° 2' 40.2\" W"}]," in DMS. North is positive, West is negative."]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Try the live converter"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["For a working interactive tool that converts DD, DMS, DDM, and UTM in real time with a map preview, use our "," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/coordinates-converter","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"Coordinates Converter"}],". Or grab your live coordinates first from "," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/my-location","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"My Location"}]," ","or "," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/gps-coordinates","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"GPS Coordinates"}],"."]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-10","children":"Related guides"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/coordinates-converter","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"Coordinates Converter (interactive tool)"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/gps-coordinates-finder","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"GPS coordinates finder — complete guide"}]}],["$","li",null,{"c